Linux File and Folder Permissions for DevOps

These are some of the most commonly used file and folder permission commands during DevOps work. Every command below includes what it does and when we use it.

Permission Basics

rwxrw-r-x file1
Represents file permissions.

Breakdown:

r = read = 4
w = write = 2
x = execute = 1

= no permission

Total permissions = 9 (3 for user, 3 for group, 3 for others)

Example:

rwx rw- r-x
user group others

Full Permission

777
Gives full permissions (read, write, execute) to user, group, and others.

755
User has full permissions, group and others have read and execute.

644
User has read and write, others have only read.

chmod Commands

chmod 777 file1
Gives full permission to file1.

chmod 777 folder1
Gives full permission to folder1.

chmod 777 folder1/*
Gives full permission to all files inside folder1.

chmod +x file1
Adds execute permission to file.

chmod -x file1
Removes execute permission.

chmod u+x file1
Adds execute permission only to user.

chmod g+w file1
Adds write permission to group.

chmod o-r file1
Removes read permission from others.

chmod 755 file1
Sets permission using numeric method.

Ownership Commands

chown username file1
Changes owner of file.

chown username:groupname file1
Changes owner and group of file.

chown username:groupname *
Changes owner and group for all files in directory.

chgrp groupname file1
Changes group of file.

chown -R username:groupname folder1
Changes ownership recursively for folder.

Ownership Format

root root
First root → user (owner)
Second root → group

User Management Commands

cat /etc/passwd
Displays all users in the system.

id username
Displays user ID, group ID, and groups.

Example:

id devuser

Output:

uid=1001(devuser) gid=1001(devuser) groups=1001(devuser)

Explanation:

uid → user ID
gid → group ID
groups → groups user belongs to

useradd devuser
Creates a new user.

When a user is created, a group is also created automatically with the same name.

su - devuser
Switches to another user.

passwd devuser
Sets or changes password for user.

Password Rules

Password should be strong
Use uppercase, lowercase, numbers, and symbols
Minimum 8 characters recommended

userdel -r devuser
Deletes user and its home directory.

Group Management Commands

cat /etc/group
Displays all groups in the system.

groupadd devgroup
Creates a new group.

groupdel devgroup
Deletes a group.

File Permission Check

ls -l
Displays file permissions, owner, and group.

Example Output:

-rwxr-xr-x 1 root root file1

Explanation:

→ file type
rwx → user permissions
r-x → group permissions
r-x → others permissions
Important Notes

User has highest priority, then group, then others
Always use correct permissions for security
Avoid using 777 in production environments
Use -R carefully (recursive changes)
Every file has an owner and a group

